#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:31
#, no-wrap
msgid "Current Linux systems have graphical utilities dedicated to the work of an administrator. However, it is important to be able to use the interface in command line mode for several reasons:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:37
#, no-wrap
msgid "The majority of system commands are common to all Linux distributions, which is not the case for graphical tools.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:37
#, no-wrap
msgid "It can happen that the system does not start correctly but that a backup command interpreter remains accessible.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:37
#, no-wrap
msgid "Remote administration is done on the command line with an SSH terminal.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:37
#, no-wrap
msgid "In order to preserve server resources, the graphical interface is either not installed or launched on demand.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:37
#, no-wrap
msgid "Administration is done by scripts.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:39
#, no-wrap
msgid "Learning these commands allows the administrator to connect to a Linux terminal, to manage its resources and files, to identify the station, the terminal, and the connected users, etc.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:40
#, no-wrap
msgid "The users"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:43
#, no-wrap
msgid "The user of a Linux system will be defined in the `/etc/passwd` file, by:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:49
#, no-wrap
msgid "A **login name**, more commonly called \"login\", containing no spaces.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:49
#, no-wrap
msgid "A numeric identifier: **UID** (User Identifier).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:49
#, no-wrap
msgid "A group identifier: **GID** (Group Identifier).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:49
#, no-wrap
msgid "A **command interpreter**, e.g., a shell, which can be different from one user to another.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:49
#, no-wrap
msgid "A **connection directory**, e.g., the __home directory__.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:51
#, no-wrap
msgid "In other files the user will be defined by:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:54
#, no-wrap
msgid "A **password**, which is encrypted before being stored (`/etc/shadow`).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:54
#, no-wrap
msgid "A **command prompt**, or __prompt__ login, which is symbolized by a `#` for administrators and a `$` for other users (`/etc/profile`).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:56
#, no-wrap
msgid "Depending on the security policy implemented on the system, the password will require a certain number of characters and meet certain complexity requirements.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:58
#, no-wrap
msgid "Among the existing command interpreters, the **Bourne-Again Shell** (`/bin/bash`) is the one most frequently used. It is assigned by default to new users. For various reasons, advanced Linux users can choose alternative shells such as the Korn Shell (`ksh`), the C Shell (`csh`), etc.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:60
#, no-wrap
msgid "The user's login directory is by convention stored in the `/home` directory of the workstation. It will contain the user's personal data and the configuration files of his applications. By default, at login, the login directory is selected as the current directory.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:62
#, no-wrap
msgid "A workstation-type installation (with graphical interface) starts this interface on terminal 1. Linux being multi-user, it is possible to connect several users several times, on different **physical terminals** (TTY) or **virtual terminals** (PTS). Virtual terminals are available within a graphical environment. A user switches from one physical terminal to another using <kbd>Alt</kbd> + <kbd>Fx</kbd> from the command line or using <kbd>CTRL</kbd> + <kbd>Alt</kbd> + <kbd>Fx</kbd>.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:63
#, no-wrap
msgid "The shell"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:66
#, no-wrap
msgid "Once the user is connected to a console, the shell displays the **command prompt**. It then behaves like an infinite loop, repeating the same pattern with each statement entered:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:74
#, no-wrap
msgid "Displays the command prompt.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:74
#, no-wrap
msgid "Reads the command.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:74
#, no-wrap
msgid "Analyzes the syntax.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:74
#, no-wrap
msgid "Substitutes special characters.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:74
#, no-wrap
msgid "Executes the command.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:74
#, no-wrap
msgid "Etc.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:76
#, no-wrap
msgid "The key sequence <kbd>CTRL</kbd> + <kbd>C</kbd> is used to interrupt a running command.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:78
#, no-wrap
msgid "The use of a command generally follows this sequence:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:79
#, no-wrap
msgid "command [option(s)] [arguments(s)]\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:84
#, no-wrap
msgid "The name of the command is often **lower case**.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:86
#, no-wrap
msgid "A space separates each item.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:89
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"**Short options** begin with a dash (`-l`), while **long options** begin with two dashes (`--list`).\n"
"A double dash (`--`) indicates the end of the option list.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:91
#, no-wrap
msgid "It is possible to group some short options together:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:92
#, no-wrap
msgid "$ ls -l -i -a\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:97
#, no-wrap
msgid "is equivalent to:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:98
#, no-wrap
msgid "$ ls -lia\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:103
#, no-wrap
msgid "There can be several arguments after an option:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:104
#, no-wrap
msgid "$ ls -lia /etc /home /var\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:109
#, no-wrap
msgid "In the literature, the term \"option\" is equivalent to the term \"parameter,\" which is more commonly used in programming. The optional side of an option or argument is symbolized by enclosing it in square brackets `[` and `]`. When more than one option is possible, a vertical bar called a \"pipe\" separates them `[a|e|i]`.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:110
#, no-wrap
msgid "General commands"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:112
#, no-wrap
msgid "`apropos`, `whatis` and `man` commands"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:115
#, no-wrap
msgid "It is impossible for an administrator at any level to know all the commands and options in detail. A manual is usually available for all installed commands.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ####
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:116
#, no-wrap
msgid "`apropos` command"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:119
#, no-wrap
msgid "The command `apropos` allows you to search by keyword within these manual pages:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:124
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"| Options                                     | Description                                               |\n"
"| ------------------------------------------- | ---------------------------------------------------------- |\n"
"| `-s`, `--sections list` or `--section list` | Limited to manual sections.                                |\n"
"| `-a` or `--and`                             | Displays only the item matching all the provided keywords. |\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:127
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ apropos clear\n"
"clear (1)            - clear the terminal screen\n"
"clear_console (1)    - clear the console\n"
"clearenv (3)         - clear the environment\n"
"clearerr (3)         - check and reset stream status\n"
"clearerr_unlocked (3) - nonlocking stdio functions\n"
"feclearexcept (3)    - floating-point rounding and exception handling\n"
"fwup_clear_status (3) - library to support management of system firmware updates\n"
"klogctl (3)          - read and/or clear kernel message ring buffer; set console_loglevel\n"
"sgt-samegame (6)     - block-clearing puzzle\n"
"syslog (2)           - read and/or clear kernel message ring buffer; set console_loglevel\n"
"timerclear (3)       - timeval operations\n"
"XClearArea (3)       - clear area or window\n"
"XClearWindow (3)     - clear area or window\n"
"XSelectionClearEvent (3) - SelectionClear event structure\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:146
#, no-wrap
msgid "To find the command that will allow changing the password of an account:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:147
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ apropos --exact password  -a change\n"
"chage (1)            - change user password expiry information\n"
"passwd (1)           - change user password\n"
msgstr ""

