#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:245
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"| Options | Comments                                                                                                           |\n"
"| ------- | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------ |\n"
"| `-w`    | Writes the current history to the history file.                                                |\n"
"| `-c`    | Deletes the history of the current session (but not the contents of the `.bash_history` file). |\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:247
#, no-wrap
msgid "Manipulating history:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:249
#, no-wrap
msgid "To manipulate the history, the following commands entered from the command prompt will:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:257
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"| Keys               | Function                                                  |\n"
"| ------------------ | --------------------------------------------------------- |\n"
"| <kbd>!!</kbd>      | Recalls the last command placed.                           |\n"
"| <kbd>!n</kbd>      | Recalls the command by its number in the list.             |\n"
"| <kbd>!string</kbd> | Recalls the most recent command beginning with the string. |\n"
"| <kbd>↑</kbd>       | Navigates through your history working backward in time from the most recent command. |\n"
"| <kbd>↓</kbd>       | Navigates through your history working forward in time. |\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:258
#, no-wrap
msgid "Auto-complete"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:261
#, no-wrap
msgid "Auto-completion is a great help.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:265
#, no-wrap
msgid "Completes commands, entered paths, or file names.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:265
#, no-wrap
msgid "Press the <kbd>TAB</kbd> key to complete the entry in the case of a single solution.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:265
#, no-wrap
msgid "In the case of multiple solutions, press <kbd>TAB</kbd> a second time to see options.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:267
#, no-wrap
msgid "If double-pressing the <kbd>TAB</kbd> key presents no options, then there is no solution to the current completion.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:268
#, no-wrap
msgid "Display and Identification"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:270
#, no-wrap
msgid "`clear` command"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:273
#, no-wrap
msgid "The `clear` command clears the contents of the terminal screen. More accurately, it shifts the display so that the command prompt is at the top of the screen on the first line.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:275
#, no-wrap
msgid "On a physical terminal, the display will be permanently hidden, whereas in a graphical interface, a scrollbar will allow you to go back in the history of the virtual terminal.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:279
#, no-wrap
msgid "    <kbd>CTRL</kbd> + <kbd>L</kbd> will have the same effect as the `clear` command\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:280
#, no-wrap
msgid "`echo` command"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:283
#, no-wrap
msgid "The `echo` command is used to display a string of characters.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:285
#, no-wrap
msgid "This command is most commonly used in administration scripts to inform the user during execution.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:287
#, no-wrap
msgid "The `-n` option indicates no newline output string (by default, newline output string).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:288
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"shell > echo -n \"123\";echo \"456\"\n"
"123456\n"
"\n"
"shell > echo \"123\";echo \"456\"\n"
"123\n"
"456\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:298
#, no-wrap
msgid "For various reasons, the script developer may need to use special sequences (starting with a `\\` character). In this case, the `-e` option will be stipulated, allowing interpretation of the sequences.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:300
#, no-wrap
msgid "Among the frequently used sequences, we can mention:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:308
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"| Sequence | Result                |\n"
"| -------- | --------------------- |\n"
"| `\\a`     | Sends a sonar beep      |\n"
"| `\\b`     | Back                  |\n"
"| `\\n`     | Adds a line break     |\n"
"| `\\t`     | Adds a horizontal tab |\n"
"| `\\v`     | Adds a vertical tab     |\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:309
#, no-wrap
msgid "`date` command"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:312
#, no-wrap
msgid "The `date` command displays the date and time. The command has the following syntax:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:313
#, no-wrap
msgid "date [-d yyyyMMdd] [format]\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:319
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ date\n"
"Mon May 24 16:46:53 CEST 2021\n"
"$ date -d 20210517 +%j\n"
"137\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:327
#, no-wrap
msgid "In this last example, the `-d` option displays a given date. The `+%j` option formats this date to show only the day of the year.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:331
#, no-wrap
msgid "    The format of a date can change depending on the value of the language defined in the environment variable `$LANG`.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:333
#, no-wrap
msgid "The date display can follow the following formats:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:353
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"| Option  | Format                                                    |\n"
"| --------| --------------------------------------------------------- |\n"
"| `+%A`   | Locale's full weekday name (e.g., Sunday)                 |\n"
"| `+%B`   | Locale's full month name (e.g., January)                  |\n"
"| `+%c`   | Locale's date and time (e.g., Thu Mar  3 23:05:25 2005)   |\n"
"| `+%d`   | Day of month (e.g., 01)                                   |\n"
"| `+%F`   | Date in `YYYY-MM-DD` format                               |\n"
"| `+%G`   | Year                                                      |\n"
"| `+%H`   | Hour (00..23)                                             |\n"
"| `+%j`   | Day of the year (001..366)                                |\n"
"| `+%m`   | Month number (01..12)                                     |\n"
"| `+%M`   | Minute  (00..59)                                          |\n"
"| `+%R`   | Time in `hh:mm` format                                    |\n"
"| `+%s`   | Seconds since January 1, 1970                             |\n"
"| `+%S`   | Second (00..60)                                           |\n"
"| `+%T`   | Time in `hh:mm:ss` format                                 |\n"
"| `+%u`   | Day of the week (`1` for Monday)                          |\n"
"| `+%V`   | Week number (`+%V`)                                       |\n"
"| `+%x`   | Date in format `DD/MM/YYYY`                               |\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:355
#, no-wrap
msgid "The `date` command also allows you to change the system date and time. In this case, the `-s` option will be used.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:356
#, no-wrap
msgid "[root]# date -s \"2021-05-24 10:19\"\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:361
#, no-wrap
msgid "The format to be used following the `-s` option is this:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:362
#, no-wrap
msgid "date -s \"yyyy-MM-dd hh:mm[:ss]\"\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:366
#, no-wrap
msgid "`id`, `who` and `whoami` commands"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:369
#, no-wrap
msgid "The `id` command is used to display information about users and groups. By default, no user parameter is added, and the information of the currently logged in user and group is displayed。\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:370
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ id rockstar\n"
"uid=1000(rockstar) gid=1000(rockstar) groups=1000(rockstar),10(wheel)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:376
#, no-wrap
msgid "The `-g`, `-G`, `-n` and `-u` options display the main group GID, subgroup GIDs, names instead of numeric identifiers, and the user's UID respectively.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:378
#, no-wrap
msgid "The `whoami` command displays the login of the current user.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:380
#, no-wrap
msgid "The `who` command alone displays the names of logged in users:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:381
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ who\n"
"rockstar tty1   2021-05-24 10:30\n"
"root     pts/0  2021-05-24 10:31\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:388
#, no-wrap
msgid "Since Linux is multi-user, it is possible that multiple sessions are open on the same station, either physically or over the network. It is interesting to know which users are logged in, if only to communicate with them by sending messages.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:391
#, no-wrap
msgid "tty: represents a terminal.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:391
#, no-wrap
msgid "pts/: represents a virtual console in a graphical environment with the number after representing the instance of the virtual console (0, 1, 2...)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:393
#, no-wrap
msgid "The `-r` option also displays the runlevel (see chapter \"startup\").\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:394
#, no-wrap
msgid "File Tree"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:397
#, no-wrap
msgid "In Linux, the file tree is an inverted tree, called a **single hierarchical tree**, whose root is the directory `/`.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:399
#, no-wrap
msgid "The **current directory** is the directory where the user is located.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:401
#, no-wrap
msgid "The **connection directory** is the working directory associated with the user. The login directories are, by default, stored in the `/home` directory.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:403
#, no-wrap
msgid "When the user logs in, the current directory is the login directory.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:405
#, no-wrap
msgid "An **absolute path** references a file from the root by traversing the entire tree to the file level:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:407
#, no-wrap
msgid "`/home/groupA/alice/file`\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:409
#, no-wrap
msgid "The **relative path** references that same file by traversing the entire tree from the current directory:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:411
#, no-wrap
msgid "`../alice/file`\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:413
#, no-wrap
msgid "In the above example, the \"`..`\" refers to the parent directory of the current directory.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:415
#, no-wrap
msgid "A directory, even if it is empty, will necessarily contain at least **two references**:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:418
#, no-wrap
msgid "`.`: reference to itself.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:418
#, no-wrap
msgid "`..`: reference to the parent directory of the current directory.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:420
#, no-wrap
msgid "A relative path can thus start with `./` or `../`. When the relative path refers to a subdirectory or file in the current directory, then the `./` is often omitted. Mentioning the first `./` in the tree will only really be required to run an executable file.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:422
#, no-wrap
msgid "Errors in paths can cause many problems: creating folders or files in the wrong places, unintentional deletions, etc. It is therefore strongly recommended to use auto-completion when entering paths.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:424
#, no-wrap
msgid "![our example tree](images/commands-pathabsolute.png)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:426
#, no-wrap
msgid "In the above example, we are looking to give the location of the file `myfile` from the directory of bob.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:429
#, no-wrap
msgid "By an **absolute path**, the current directory does not matter. We start at the root, and work our way down to the directories `home`, `groupA`, `alice` and finally the file `myfile`: `/home/groupA/alice/myfile`.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:429
#, no-wrap
msgid "By a **relative path**, our starting point being the current directory `bob`, we go up one level through `..` (i.e., into the `groupA` directory), then down into the alice directory, and finally the `myfile` file: `../alice/myfile`.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:430
#, no-wrap
msgid "`pwd` command"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:433
#, no-wrap
msgid "The `pwd` (Print Working Directory) command displays the absolute path of the current directory.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:434
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ pwd\n"
"/home/rockstar\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:440
#, no-wrap
msgid "To use a relative path to reference a file or directory, or use the `cd` command to move to another directory, you must know its location in the file tree.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:442
#, no-wrap
msgid "Depending on the type of shell and the different parameters of its configuration file, the terminal prompt (also known as the command prompt) will display the absolute or relative path of the current directory.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:443
#, no-wrap
msgid "`cd` command"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:446
#, no-wrap
msgid "The `cd` (Change Directory) command allows you to change the current directory -- in other words, to move through the tree.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:447
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ cd /tmp\n"
"$ pwd\n"
"/tmp\n"
"$ cd ../\n"
"$ pwd\n"
"/\n"
"$ cd\n"
"$ pwd\n"
"/home/rockstar\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:460
#, no-wrap
msgid "As you can see in the last example above, the command `cd` with no arguments moves the current directory to the `home directory`.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:461
#, no-wrap
msgid "`ls` command"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:464
#, no-wrap
msgid "The `ls` command displays the contents of a directory.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:465
#, no-wrap
msgid "ls [-a] [-i] [-l] [directory1] [directory2] […]\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:471
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ ls /home\n"
".    ..    rockstar\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:477
#, no-wrap
msgid "The main options of the `ls` command are:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:483
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"| Option                                                       | Information                                                                                                                          |\n"
"| ------------------------------------------------------------ | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------ |\n"
"| `-a`                                                         | Displays all files, even hidden ones. Hidden files in Linux are those beginning with `.`.                                            |\n"
"| `-i`                                                         | Displays inode numbers.                                                                                                              |\n"
"| `-l`                                                         | Use a long listing format, that is, each line displays long format information for a file or directory.                                 |\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:485
#, no-wrap
msgid "The `ls` command, however, has a lot of options (see `man`):\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:496
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"| Option                                                       | Information                                                                                                                          |\n"
"| ------                                                       | ------------                                                                                                                         |\n"
"| `-d`                                                         | Displays information about a directory instead of listing its contents.                                                              |\n"
"| `-g`                                                         | Like -l option, but do not list owner.                                                                                               |\n"
"| `-h`                                                         | Displays file sizes in the most appropriate format (byte, kilobyte, megabyte, gigabyte, ...). `h` stands for Human Readable. Needs to be used with -l option.         |\n"
"| `-s`                                                         | Displays the allocated size of each file, in blocks. In the GNU/Linux operating system, \"block\" is the smallest unit of storage in the file system, one block equals 4096Byte. |\n"
"| `-A`                                                         | Displays all files in the directory except `.` and `..`                                                                              |\n"
"| `-R`                                                         | Displays the contents of subdirectories recursively.                                                                                 |\n"
"| `-F`                                                         | Displays the type of files. Prints a `/` for a directory, `*` for executables, `@` for a symbolic link, and nothing for a text file. |\n"
"| `-X`                                                         | Sorts files according to their extensions.                                                                                           |\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:498
#, no-wrap
msgid "Description of columns generated by running the `ls -lia` command:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:499
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ ls -lia /home\n"
"78489 drwx------ 4 rockstar rockstar 4096 25 oct. 08:10 rockstar\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:514
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"| Value           | Information                                                                                                   |\n"
"| --------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |\n"
"| `78489`         | Inode Number.                                                                                                 |\n"
"| `drwx------`    | File type (`d`) and rights (`rwx------`).                                                                     |\n"
"| `4`             | Number of subdirectories (`.` and `..` included). For a file, it represents the number of hard links, and 1 represents itself. |\n"
"| `rockstar`      | User ownership.                                                                                               |\n"
"| `rockstar`      | Group ownership.                                                                                              |\n"
"| `4096`          | For files, it shows the size of the file. For directories, it shows the fixed value of 4096 bytes occupied by the file naming. To calculate the total size of a directory, use `du -sh rockstar/` |\n"
"| `25 oct. 08:10` | Last modified date.                                                                                           |\n"
"| `rockstar`      | The name of the file (or directory).                                                                          |\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:518
#, no-wrap
msgid "    **Aliases** are frequently positioned in common distributions.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:520
#, no-wrap
msgid "    This is the case of the alias `ll`:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:524
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    ```\n"
"    alias ll='ls -l --color=auto'\n"
"    ```\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:526
#, no-wrap
msgid "The `ls` command has many options. Here are some advanced examples of uses:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:528
#, no-wrap
msgid "List the files in `/etc` in order of last modification:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:529
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ ls -ltr /etc\n"
"total 1332\n"
"-rw-r--r--.  1 root root    662 29 may   2021 logrotate.conf\n"
"-rw-r--r--.  1 root root    272 17 may.   2021 mailcap\n"
"-rw-------.  1 root root    122 12 may.  2021 securetty\n"
"...\n"
"-rw-r--r--.  2 root root     85 18 may.  17:04 resolv.conf\n"
"-rw-r--r--.  1 root root     44 18 may.  17:04 adjtime\n"
"-rw-r--r--.  1 root root    283 18 may.  17:05 mtab\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:542
#, no-wrap
msgid "List `/var` files larger than 1 megabyte but less than 1 gigabyte. The example here uses advanced `grep` commands with regular expressions. Novices don't have to struggle too much, there will be a special tutorial to introduce these regular expressions in the future.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:543
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ ls -lhR /var/ | grep ^\\- | grep -E \"[1-9]*\\.[0-9]*M\" \n"
"...\n"
"-rw-r--r--. 1 apache apache 1.2M 10 may.  13:02 XB RiyazBdIt.ttf\n"
"-rw-r--r--. 1 apache apache 1.2M 10 may.  13:02 XB RiyazBd.ttf\n"
"-rw-r--r--. 1 apache apache 1.1M 10 may.  13:02 XB RiyazIt.ttf\n"
"...\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:553
#, no-wrap
msgid "Of course, we highly recommend that you use the `find` command.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:554
#, no-wrap
msgid "$ find /var -size +1M -a -size -1024M  -a -type f  -exec ls -lh {} \\;\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:559
#, no-wrap
msgid "Show the rights on a folder:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:561
#, no-wrap
msgid "To find out the rights to a folder, in our example `/etc`, the following command would **not** be appropriate:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:562
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ ls -l /etc\n"
"total 1332\n"
