#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:610
#, no-wrap
msgid "`mkdir` command"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:613
#, no-wrap
msgid "The `mkdir` command creates a directory or directory tree.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:614
#, no-wrap
msgid "mkdir [-p] directory [directory] [...]\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:620
#, no-wrap
msgid "$ mkdir /home/rockstar/work\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:625
#, no-wrap
msgid "The \"rockstar\" directory must exist to create the \"work\" directory.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:627
#, no-wrap
msgid "Otherwise, the `-p` option should be used. The `-p` option creates the parent directories if they do not exist.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:631
#, no-wrap
msgid "    It is not recommended to use Linux command names as directory or file names.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:632
#, no-wrap
msgid "`touch` command"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:635
#, no-wrap
msgid "The `touch` command changes the timestamp of a file or creates an empty file if the file does not exist.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:636
#, no-wrap
msgid "touch [-t date] file\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:642
#, no-wrap
msgid "$ touch /home/rockstar/myfile\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:649
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"| Option                            | Information                                                                |\n"
"| --------------------------------- | -------------------------------------------------------------------------- |\n"
"| `-t date`                         | Changes the date of last modification of the file with the specified date. |\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:651
#, no-wrap
msgid "Date format: `[AAAA]MMJJhhmm[ss]`\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:655
#, no-wrap
msgid "    The `touch` command is primarily used to create an empty file, but it can be useful for incremental or differential backups for example. Indeed, the only effect of executing a `touch` on a file will be to force it to be saved during the next backup.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:656
#, no-wrap
msgid "`rmdir` command"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:659
#, no-wrap
msgid "The `rmdir` command deletes an empty directory.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:662
#, no-wrap
msgid "$ rmdir /home/rockstar/work\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:669
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"| Option                                                                  | Information |\n"
"| ----------------------------------------------------------------------- | ----------- |\n"
"| `-p` |  Removes the parent directory or directories provided if they are empty.           |\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:673
#, no-wrap
msgid "    To delete both a non-empty directory and its contents, use the `rm` command.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:674
#, no-wrap
msgid "`rm` command"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:677
#, no-wrap
msgid "The `rm` command deletes a file or directory.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:678
#, no-wrap
msgid "rm [-f] [-r] file [file] [...]\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:685
#, no-wrap
msgid "    Any deletion of a file or directory is final.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:691
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"| Options | Information                              |\n"
"| ------- | ---------------------------------------- |\n"
"| `-f`    | Do not ask whether to delete. |\n"
"| `-i`    | Ask whether to delete.       |\n"
"| `-r`    | Delete a directory and recursively delete its subdirectories.      |\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:695
#, no-wrap
msgid "    The `rm` command itself does not ask for confirmation when deleting files. However, with a Red Hat/Rocky distribution, `rm` does ask for confirmation of deletion because the `rm` command is an `alias` of the `rm -i` command. Don't be surprised if on another distribution, like Debian for example, you don't get a confirmation request.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:697
#, no-wrap
msgid "Deleting a folder with the `rm` command, whether the folder is empty or not, will require the `-r` option to be added.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:699
#, no-wrap
msgid "The end of the options is signaled to the shell by a double dash `--`.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:701
#, no-wrap
msgid "In the example:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:702
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ >-hard-hard # To create an empty file called -hard-hard\n"
"hard-hard\n"
"[CTRL+C] To interrupt the creation of the file\n"
"$ rm -f -- -hard-hard\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:710
#, no-wrap
msgid "The hard-hard file name starts with a `-`. Without the use of the `--` the shell would have interpreted the `-d` in `-hard-hard` as an option.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:711
#, no-wrap
msgid "`mv` command"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:714
#, no-wrap
msgid "The `mv` command moves and renames a file.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:715
#, no-wrap
msgid "mv file [file ...] destination\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:721
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ mv /home/rockstar/file1 /home/rockstar/file2\n"
"$ mv /home/rockstar/file1 /home/rockstar/file2 /tmp\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:730
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"| Options                                                                        | Information                                                     |\n"
"| ------------------------------------------------------------------------------ | --------------------------------------------------------------- |\n"
"| `-f`                                                                           | Don't ask for confirmation if overwriting the destination file. |\n"
"| `-i`                                                                           | Request confirmation if overwriting destination file (default). |\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:732
#, no-wrap
msgid "A few concrete cases will help you understand the difficulties that can arise:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:733
#, no-wrap
msgid "$ mv /home/rockstar/file1 /home/rockstar/file2\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:738
#, no-wrap
msgid "Renames `file1` to `file2`. If `file2` already exists, replace the contents of the file with `file1`.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:739
#, no-wrap
msgid "$ mv /home/rockstar/file1 /home/rockstar/file2 /tmp\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:744
#, no-wrap
msgid "Moves `file1` and `file2` into the `/tmp` directory.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:745
#, no-wrap
msgid "$ mv file1 /repexist/file2\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:750
#, no-wrap
msgid "Moves `file1` into `repexist` and renames it `file2`.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:751
#, no-wrap
msgid "$ mv file1 file2\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:756
#, no-wrap
msgid "`file1` is renamed to `file2`.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:757
#, no-wrap
msgid "$ mv file1 /repexist\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:762
#, no-wrap
msgid "If the destination directory exists, `file1` is moved to `/repexist`.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:763
#, no-wrap
msgid "$ mv file1 /wrongrep\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:768
#, no-wrap
msgid "If the destination directory does not exist, `file1` is renamed to `wrongrep` in the root directory.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:769
#, no-wrap
msgid "`cp` command"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:772
#, no-wrap
msgid "The `cp` command copies a file.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:773
#, no-wrap
msgid "cp file [file ...] destination\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:779
#, no-wrap
msgid "$ cp -r /home/rockstar /tmp\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:790
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"| Options | Information                                                      |\n"
"| ------- | ---------------------------------------------------------------- |\n"
"| `-i`    | Request confirmation if overwriting (default).                   |\n"
"| `-f`    | Do not ask for confirmation if overwriting the destination file. |\n"
"| `-p`    | Keeps the owner, permissions and timestamp of the copied file.   |\n"
"| `-r`    | Copies a directory with its files and subdirectories.            |\n"
"| `-s`    | Creates a symbolic link rather than copying.                    |\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:791
#, no-wrap
msgid "cp file1 /repexist/file2\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:796
#, no-wrap
msgid "`file1` is copied to `/repexist` under the name `file2`.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:797
#, no-wrap
msgid "$ cp file1 file2\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:802
#, no-wrap
msgid "`file1` is copied as `file2` to this directory.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:803
#, no-wrap
msgid "$ cp file1 /repexist\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:808
#, no-wrap
msgid "If the destination directory exists, `file1` is copied to `/repexist`.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:809
#, no-wrap
msgid "$ cp file1 /wrongrep\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:814
#, no-wrap
msgid "If the destination directory does not exist, `file1` is copied under the name `wrongrep` to the root directory.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:815
#, no-wrap
msgid "Visualization"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:817
#, no-wrap
msgid "`file` command"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:820
#, no-wrap
msgid "The `file` command displays the type of a file.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:821
#, no-wrap
msgid "file file1 [files]\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:827
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ file /etc/passwd /etc\n"
"/etc/passwd:    ASCII text\n"
"/etc:        directory\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:833
#, no-wrap
msgid "`more` command"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:836
#, no-wrap
msgid "The `more` command displays the contents of one or more files screen by screen.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:837
#, no-wrap
msgid "more file1 [files]\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:843
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ more /etc/passwd\n"
"root:x:0:0:root:/root:/bin/bash\n"
"...\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:850
#, no-wrap
msgid "Using the <kbd>ENTER</kbd> key, the move is line by line. Using the <kbd>SPACE</kbd> key, the move is page by page. `/text` allows you to search for the occurrence in the file.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:851
#, no-wrap
msgid "`less` command"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:854
#, no-wrap
msgid "The `less` command displays the contents of one or more files. The `less` command is interactive and has its own commands for use.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:855
#, no-wrap
msgid "less file1 [files]\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:860
#, no-wrap
msgid "The commands specific to `less` are:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:871
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"| Command           | Action                                          |\n"
"| ----------------- | ----------------------------------------------- |\n"
"| <kbd>h</kbd>               | Help.                                           |\n"
"| <kbd>↑</kbd><kbd>↓</kbd><kbd>→</kbd><kbd>←</kbd>         | Move up, down a line, or to the right or left.  |\n"
"| <kbd>Enter</kbd>           | Move down one line.                             |\n"
"| <kbd>Space</kbd>           | Move down one page.                             |\n"
"| <kbd>PgUp</kbd> and <kbd>PgDn</kbd> | Move up or down one page.                       |\n"
"| <kbd>gg</kbd> and <kbd>G</kbd> | Move to the first and last pages         |\n"
"| `/text`           | Search for text.                                |\n"
"| <kbd>q</kbd>               | Quit the `less` command.                        |\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:872
#, no-wrap
msgid "`cat` command"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:875
#, no-wrap
msgid "The `cat` command concatenates the contents of multiple files and displays the result on the standard output.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:876
#, no-wrap
msgid "cat file1 [files]\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:881
#, no-wrap
msgid "Example 1 - Displaying the contents of a file to the standard output:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:882
#, no-wrap
msgid "$ cat /etc/passwd\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:887
#, no-wrap
msgid "Example 2 - Displaying the contents of multiple files to standard output:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:888
#, no-wrap
msgid "$ cat /etc/passwd /etc/group\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:893
#, no-wrap
msgid "Example 3 - Combining the contents of multiple files into one file using output redirection:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:894
#, no-wrap
msgid "$ cat /etc/passwd /etc/group > usersAndGroups.txt\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:899
#, no-wrap
msgid "Example 4 - Displaying the line numbering:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:900
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ cat -n /etc/profile\n"
"     1    # /etc/profile: system-wide .profile file for the Bourne shell (sh(1))\n"
"     2    # and Bourne compatible shells (bash(1), ksh(1), ash(1), ...).\n"
"     3\n"
"     4    if [ \"`id -u`\" -eq 0 ]; then\n"
"     5      PATH=\"/usr/local/sbin:/usr/local/bin:/usr/sbin:/usr/bin:/sbin:/bin\"\n"
"     6    else\n"
"…\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:912
#, no-wrap
msgid "Example 5 - Shows the numbering of non-empty lines:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:913
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ cat -b /etc/profile\n"
"     1    # /etc/profile: system-wide .profile file for the Bourne shell (sh(1))\n"
"     2    # and Bourne compatible shells (bash(1), ksh(1), ash(1), ...).\n"
"\n"
"     3    if [ \"`id -u`\" -eq 0 ]; then\n"
"     4      PATH=\"/usr/local/sbin:/usr/local/bin:/usr/sbin:/usr/bin:/sbin:/bin\"\n"
"     5    else\n"
"…\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:924
#, no-wrap
msgid "`tac` command"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:927
#, no-wrap
msgid "The `tac` command does almost the opposite of the `cat` command. It displays the contents of a file starting from the end (which is particularly interesting for reading logs!).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:929
#, no-wrap
msgid "Example: Display a log file by displaying the last line first:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:930
#, no-wrap
msgid "[root]# tac /var/log/messages | less\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:934
#, no-wrap
msgid "`head` command"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:937
#, no-wrap
msgid "The `head` command displays the beginning of a file.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:938
#, no-wrap
msgid "head [-n x] file\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:945
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"| Option                                                                                                | Description                            |\n"
"| ----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- | --------------------------------------- |\n"
"| `-n x`                                                                                                | Display the first `x` lines of the file |\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:947
#, no-wrap
msgid "By default (without the `-n` option), the `head` command will display the first 10 lines of the file.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:948
#, no-wrap
msgid "`tail` command"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:951
#, no-wrap
msgid "The `tail` command displays the end of a file.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:952
#, no-wrap
msgid "tail [-f] [-n x] file\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:960
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"| Option   | Description                             |\n"
"| -------- | ----------------------------------------- |\n"
"| `-n x`   | Displays the last `x` lines of the file   |\n"
"| `-f`     | Displays changes to the file in real time |\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:963
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"tail -n 3 /etc/passwd\n"
"sshd:x:74:74:Privilege-separeted sshd:/var/empty /sshd:/sbin/nologin\n"
"tcpdump::x:72:72::/:/sbin/nologin\n"
"user1:x:500:500:grp1:/home/user1:/bin/bash\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:971
#, no-wrap
msgid "With the `-f` option, the change information of the file will always be output unless the user exits the monitoring state with <kbd>CTRL</kbd> + <kbd>C</kbd>. This option is very frequently used to track log files (the logs) in real time.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:973
#, no-wrap
msgid "Without the `-n` option, the `tail` command displays the last 10 lines of the file.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:974
#, no-wrap
msgid "`sort` command"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:977
#, no-wrap
msgid "The `sort` command sorts the lines of a file.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:979
#, no-wrap
msgid "It allows you to order the result of a command or the content of a file in a given order, numerically, alphabetically, by size (KB, MB, GB) or in reverse order.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:980
#, no-wrap
msgid "sort [-k] [-n] [-u] [-o file] [-t] file\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:986
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ sort -k 3,4 -t \":\" -n /etc/passwd\n"
"root:x:0:0:root:/root:/bin/bash\n"
"adm:x:3:4:adm:/var/adm/:/sbin/nologin\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1000
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"| Option    | Description                              |\n"
"| --------- | ------------------------------------------- |\n"
"| `-k`     | Specify the columns to be separated. You can specify multiple columns.         |\n"
"| `-n`      | Requests a numeric sort.                     |\n"
"| `-o file` | Saves the sort to the specified file.        |\n"
"| `-t`     | Specify a delimiter, which requires that the contents of the corresponding file must be regularly delimited column contents, otherwise they cannot be sorted properly. |\n"
"| `-r`      | Reverse the order of the result. Used in conjunction with the `-n` option to sort in order from largest to smallest.             |\n"
"| `-u`     | Remove duplicates after sorting. Equivalent to `sort file | uniq`.                   |\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1002
#, no-wrap
msgid "The `sort` command sorts the file only on the screen. The file is not modified by the sorting. To save the sort, use the `-o` option or an output redirection `>`.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1004
#, no-wrap
msgid "By default, the numbers are sorted according to their character. Thus, \"110\" will be before \"20\", which will itself be before \"3\". The `-n` option must be specified so that the numeric character blocks are sorted by their value.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1006
#, no-wrap
msgid "The `sort` command reverses the order of the results, with the `-r` option:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1007
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"$ sort -k 3 -t \":\" -n -r /etc/passwd\n"
"nobody:x:65534:65534:Kernel Overflow User:/:/sbin/nologin\n"
"systemd-coredump:x:999:997:systemd Core Dumper:/:/sbin/nologin\n"
"polkitd:x:998:996:User for polkitd:/:/sbin/nologin\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1015
#, no-wrap
msgid "In this example, the `sort` command will sort the contents of the `/etc/passwd` file this time from largest uid (user identifier) to smallest.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1017
#, no-wrap
msgid "Some advanced examples of using the `sort` command:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1019
#, no-wrap
msgid "Shuffling values\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1021
#, no-wrap
msgid "The `sort` command also allows you to shuffle values with the `-R` option:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1022
#, no-wrap
msgid "$ sort -R /etc/passwd\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1027
#, no-wrap
msgid "Sorting IP addresses\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1029
#, no-wrap
msgid "A system administrator is quickly confronted with the processing of IP addresses from the logs of his services such as SMTP, VSFTP or Apache. These addresses are typically extracted with the `cut` command.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1031
#, no-wrap
msgid "Here is an example with the file `dns-client.txt`:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1032
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"192.168.1.10\n"
"192.168.1.200\n"
"5.1.150.146\n"
"208.128.150.98\n"
"208.128.150.99\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/03-commands.md:1040
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
